 1/n https://t.co/sas1Up3ckD

Crypto gas isn't the best label. Most folk have a good idea of what 'gas' is in their minds, so the idea that #Ethereum  costs gas doesn't really compute for the average Joe. 

Which is totally fair. 

In crypto, gas is an abstract concept. 2/n

So you'll need to take a minute to divorce your current understanding of 'gas' and make mental space for an analogous definition.

I'll give you a sec.

*waiting*

*waiting intensifies*

3/n https://t.co/alhdkvGrYt

Done? Sweet. lfg

Simply put gas is a make belief unit of account. 

And the 'price' of gas is an estimated transaction fee.

4/n

It's called gas because its kinda like gas in a car. Ethereum is the car. And the #EVM  is the engine. In order to work the EVM ~theoretically~ burns gas. 

Nothing is actually being burned though. 

5/n

But in order to work, the EVM needs ether to incentivize miners to execute transactions when they're requested.

Why do we need 'gas' then?

Couldn't miners just skim their cut off each transaction of Eth and call it a day? 6/n

Ya they could. But it would be ~arguably~ more confusing to do it that way. 

Gas allows Ethereum and us to evaluate transaction fees separately from the price of Eth itself.  7/n

It's a bit arbitrary, but think about the flexibility it allows for monitoring transactional efficiency distinctly from the value of ETH itself.

Without 'gas' we would need to lump the cost of transactions and the price of eth together. 8/n

Ethereum miners make money (ETH) not only by mining ether, but confirming transactions. These miners are incentivized to add blocks to the blockchain with a certain amount of ether that is calculated at the time of the transaction. 9/n

Gas prices are theoretically dependant on the amount of effort it takes miners to validate the transaction. 

'Effort' is a product of computational power and storage. 10/n

Sidebar: gas isn't denoted in Eth. That's bc it would be a pain in the bum to write out all those decimals. 

So instead, gas is accounted in gwei. Wei is the smallest unit of account for Eth. 

One wei = E/10^18. 

Gas is expressed in gweiâ€”1 billion wei = giga-wei=gwei.

11/n

So why do gas prices vary so much? 

And how come they aren't dialled in when a transaction is requested?  12/n https://t.co/gsXytiYYhd

If you've dealt with eth in the past few months you were probably sadface.jpg to see how much it cost to buy and sell stuff.

Here's another screenshot from the @doodles mint last night. 13/n https://t.co/rpoLzUSY0l

People are paying the equivalent to thousands of USD for a single transaction. 

Which is a tough pill to swallow when you're buying something that might only be worth a few hundred USD.

14/n

So where does this volatilty come from? Can't these silly miners just charge us a flat fee and leave us alone?

The price of gas is dictated by the consensus protocol of the Ethereum network AND the traffic on the network. In other words: supply and command for blocks. 15/n

There's only so many miners, so the amount of people trying to transact on the network is what drives price. 

Miners have more incentive to process transactions with higher gas limits because, well, mo money. Don't hate the playa. Hate the game. 16/n https://t.co/DcjICc7UCU

And many do hate the game: the PoW game. The problem with Ethereum is that it currently relies on PoW consensus, which is super energy intensive. 

PoW is unsustainable for dynamic network like Ethereum because it's a perpetually exploding rocketship of innovation. 17/n

The growth of DeFi and NFTs have put a huge strain on the network as new actors pile in to new applications being built everyday.

And you might be wondering, why doesn't #Bitcoin have this problem? 18/n

This is a tech/cultural thing that goes outside of this article, but the long and the short of it is Bitcoin's conservative culture means it can't innovate or progress.

Very few things are built on Bitcoin. 19/n
So its miners process comparatively fewer transactions, which means transactions don't cost as much. 20/n https://t.co/1rIHNY8am1

Is there an end to high gas prices in sight?

The price of gas is costing Ethereum big time. 

New, agile players are entering the stage with much lower transaction fees. Affectionately known as Eth Killers (EKs). 21/n

These EKs are gaining popularity bc people won't stomach these costs.

It's impossible to know how many people are being turned away at the gate right now, but it's crippling Eth's ability to become the medium of exchange it's meant to be. 22/n

It's like showing up to the world's greatest carnival only to be charged $100 for every step you take. 

Fortunately, help is on the way. And cheaper transaction fees are right around the corner. 23/n https://t.co/lz7oHlfrir
It's important to remember how early we are. If you remember the early days of the internet, you'll recall how absurdly slow it was. 24/n

Within the next 6-12 months gas is going to plummet. Ethereum will transition to Proof of Stake. And L2s will make L1 scaling look comical.

So have faith, fren.

Gas is high, but it's the high cost of living for getting in so early on the future.
